GPCC Monitoring product

2023-04-12

This example focuses on East Africa (Somalia, Eritrea, Ethiopia). For the period 1981-2010, the time series (cells) with standard deviation below 0.5mm are identified.

Results:

This analysis shows that for East Africa the SPI values based on GPCC are not reliable. Most of East Africa presents cells (time series) with low standard deviation (at least six monthy time series). Similar results apply when one considers the period 1991-2020.

Plots

The following plots involve only the grid cells for which six or more monthly time series have standard deviation below 0.5 mm.

This plot shows the time series for each grid cell, on monthly basis.

ggplot(data=lmydf %>% filter(cell %in% zz[zz$numero>NUMERO,]$cell),aes(x=name,y=value))+
  geom_line(aes(colour=cell,group=cell))+
  facet_wrap(~mm,scales = "free")+
  theme_bw()

This plot shows the time series for each grid cell.

purrr::walk(zz[zz$numero>NUMERO,]$cell,.f=function(.cell){
  ggplot(data=lmydf %>% filter(cell %in% .cell),aes(x=name,y=value))+
    geom_line(aes(group=cell))+
    facet_wrap(~cell,scales = "free")+
    theme_bw()->grafico
  print(grafico)
})

This plot shows the grid cells with standard deviation below 0.5 mm.

lmydf[!(lmydf$cell %in% zz[zz$numero>NUMERO,]$cell),]$value<-NA
rast(lmydf %>% filter(mm==1) %>% select(x,y,value))->finale
finale[!is.na(finale)]<-1
